<TITLE> Nine named as Ekushey Award winners for 2008 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 10 (bdnews24.com)  The government has decided to honour nine people with the national Ekushey Award this year, six of them to be honoured posthumously. Chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed has approved the recommendations of the advisory council committee on national awards to accord the nine with the prestigious prize, a government official said. The chief adviser will hand out the awards on Feb 20. Professor Muzaffer Ahmad, chairman of Transparency International Bangladesh board of trustees, noted social scientist Najma Chowdhury and music director Khandaker Nurul Alam are among those who will receive this year's award. The six who are to be awarded posthumously are Dr Zohra Begum Kazi, the first woman in South Asia to gain a MBBS degree, journalist and music legend Wahidul Huq, Mymensingh Language Movement veteran Khaleque Newaj, and popular Chittagong folk singers Shyamsundar Baishnaba and Shefali Ghosh. Sylhet poet Dilwar Hossain Khan has also been nominated for the award. Diverse organisations, forums and individuals submitted 81 names after the government posted advertisements seeking names deserving of 2008's Ekushey Award. A four-member scrutiny committee, led by former cultural affairs adviser Ayub Quadri, made a primary shortlist of 15 names. Other members of the committee included the education secretary, information secretary and cultural affairs secretary. The advisory council committee on the national award nomination led by adviser Iftekhar Ahmed Chowdhury made a final list and recommended the final nine names for the 2008 Ekushey Awards. Each of the nine award winners will get a gold medal, a trophy and Tk 40,000 in cash. According to national award rules, the Ekushey Award may be conferred on up to 15 people in any one year. bdnews24.c
